<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of VAT of the Czech Republic and Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Preface</seg>
<seg id="3">The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, stresses that the courts of auditors are empowered to audit all public finances.</seg>
<seg id="4">The declaration requires that the courts of auditors have the power to examine the tax collection as much as possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">The organisation of European supreme audit institutions (EUROSAI) regards taxes as an important component of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">The thematic focus of the sixth EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenues by the court of auditors.</seg>
<seg id="7">One of the most important steps on the way to optimizing the audit activities of a court of Auditors is the development of a special strategy for the audit of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="8">This is especially true for taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.</seg>
<seg id="9">As the national economies are increasingly interlinked and interdependent, a Situation may arise in which the National Audit offices can only carry out their audit work in cooperation with the audit offices of other countries.</seg>
<seg id="10">As an example, the examination of internationally organized fraud can be considered, which can lead to significant revenue losses in many states.</seg>
<seg id="11">Cooperation between the authorities is required in the fight against such crimes.</seg>
<seg id="12">Courts of auditors that audit in this area must be prepared to cooperate closely with each other.</seg>
<seg id="13">The idea for an examination of the value added tax and the MIAS system originated at the 6th EUROSAI Congress in Bonn. This audit was carried out in cooperation between the court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Audit Office.</seg>
<seg id="14">In the course of thorough preparation, the participating audit offices first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and procedures of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">On the basis of the evaluation of the available information, we selected the subjects for the examination planning.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving the efficient and effective management of VAT is a long-standing Problem and individual states (especially the EC member states) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT and create greater transparency in this area.</seg>
<seg id="17">We are convinced that the results of our audit will not only contribute to improving the work of the financial administration, but can also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of VAT of the Czech Republic and Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Reference number: CZ) 06/27 (de) VIII 2 – 2005 – 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Subject of examination -:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) administration of VAT after the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(En) examination of administrative cooperation in the field of Value Added Tax pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) no 1798/2003 and 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">the commission's audit objective:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) the purpose of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the tax administration in the field of Value Added Tax following the Integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter “EC”) with free movement of goods and services and the use of MIAS1, in particular the control of the use of the VAT exemption for intra - community deliveries.</seg>
<seg id="26">(DE) The purpose of the audit was to examine the system of intra-community VAT control with a focus on administrative assistance in the field of VAT in accordance with the above-mentioned regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">As a result of the audit, vulnerabilities should be identified and recommendations made to remedy them.</seg>
<seg id="28">VAT information exchange system the audits were carried out jointly by the court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("Nkú") and the Federal Audit Office ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany on the basis of an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006. </seg>
<seg id="29">The cooperation focused on the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of information obtained through international administrative assistance between the financial administrations and the comparison of VAT management systems in the two countries.</seg>
<seg id="30">A joint final report on the results of the audits has been prepared in accordance with European Guideline No. 31 on the implementation of INTOSAI audit standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The period under review covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005. </seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of results and evaluation of parallel testing</seg>
<seg id="33">The parallel audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two accounting offices.</seg>
<seg id="34">In addition to the focus on "information exchange" in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) no 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) no 1925/2004, other closely related aspects were also examined, such as the registration of taxpayers, tax returns and summary declarations.</seg>
<seg id="35">In addition, the audit also covered the legal situation regarding cross-border passenger transport by bus and the comparison of statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">When comparing the systems of VAT administrations in the two states, differences were found in the following areas::</seg>
