<p>
<seg id="1">Public procurement of construction services and Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="2">Joint report of the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits</seg>
<seg id="3">Introduction and Overview</seg>
<seg id="4">The award of services by contracting authorities is of great importance for the state as well as for the economy.</seg>
<seg id="5">The state has the task to use public funds as economically and economically as possible and to ensure fair and regulated competition.</seg>
<seg id="6">In the European Union (EU), the award of services by contracting authorities is an important element in the creation of a single Economic Area.</seg>
<seg id="7">In order to be able to guarantee largely unlimited competition across borders, contracting authorities must comply with EU requirements for their contracts above certain value limits (thresholds).</seg>
<seg id="8">To this end, the EU member states have to transfer and apply the EU procurement law into national law.</seg>
<seg id="9">This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.</seg>
<seg id="10">Below the EU thresholds, it is up to the individual countries to regulate the awarding of public contracts themselves.</seg>
<seg id="11">The award of services is also a corruption-prone area.</seg>
<seg id="12">Due to the fundamentally high potential for damage, the contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue advantages in the award of their contracts.</seg>
<seg id="13">In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to conduct parallel audits on the EU-wide award of construction services as well as on corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="14">The focus of the audits was on the application of the EU procurement law, which has been transposed into national regulations, as well as preventing corruption in the award of construction services in building construction and road construction or transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="15">The awards below the EU thresholds were also included in the considerations in order to prevent corruption.</seg>
<seg id="16">The audit results of both audit courts are summarised in this joint report.</seg>
<seg id="17">The report should also be addressed to international institutions, such as the International Organization of supreme audit institutions (INTOSAI).</seg>
<seg id="18">Audit areas and audited bodies the evaluations of the Federal Court of auditors on the listed topics are mainly based on cross - sectional audits that it carried out in 2011/2012 with the building administrations responsible for the Federal Road and building construction in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="19">He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and large building projects.</seg>
<seg id="20">In addition, the Federal Audit Office used results from previous investigations.</seg>
<seg id="21">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on examination findings from the years 2008 to 2011. The tests included construction measures in road construction, railway infrastructure construction, hydraulic engineering, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) as well as other construction sectors in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="22">In Germany, the public contracts awarded by the federal government are mainly carried out by the building administrations of the federal states.</seg>
<seg id="23">In the Czech Republic, the State Building administration is centrally responsible for awarding contracts in the field of transport infrastructure.</seg>
<seg id="24">In building construction, the awards are carried out decentrally by those bodies that use state budget funds.</seg>
<seg id="25">In both countries, freelancers are also involved for parts of the procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="26">When comparing the evaluations, differences in the procurement law and in the market structure for construction services of both countries must be taken into account.</seg>
<seg id="27">Development of Public Procurement Law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="28">In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.</seg>
<seg id="29">Procurement procedures limited to the national field are governed by budgetary law and the administrative regulations based on it.</seg>
<seg id="30">For both EU-wide and national procurement, many additional individual regulations are also specified by internal administrative provisions,</seg>
<seg id="31">such as the so-called" procurement manuals " of the federal government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or more precisely formulated in compliance with procurement law case law.</seg>
<seg id="32">In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the Procurement Act and other statutory provisions which apply both to the area above and below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="33">The procurement law was significantly amended in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="34">The new regulation increased transparency in the handling of public funds, enabled greater competition and limited the possibilities of corruption in the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="35">Principles of Public Procurement Law in both countries</seg>
<seg id="36">In both countries, the open procedure, the restricted procedure and the negotiated procedure are to be used in particular for EU-wide contracts.</seg>
<seg id="37">In Germany, the National Award types (public tender, restricted tender, open tender) are to be used for Measures below the EU threshold, but these largely correspond to the EU-wide award types mentioned above.</seg>
<seg id="38">Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of priority of the open procedure (for EU-wide contracts) and the public tender (for national contracts).</seg>
<seg id="39">In the open procedure and in the public tender, any interested company can submit an offer.</seg>
<seg id="40">Another essential feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized companies.</seg>
<seg id="41">Above all, the division of an overall construction project into specialist and partial lots serves this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="42">The individual award of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.</seg>
<seg id="43">Both of the aforementioned features of German public procurement law are proven instruments for achieving economic results.</seg>
<seg id="44">More than 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees are active in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="45">In the Czech Republic, EU-wide procurement procedures are also applicable to construction projects below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="46">An exception here is the simplified procedure, in which a less stringent procedure may be used below the thresholds and under certain conditions.</seg>
<seg id="47">Czech public procurement law, in accordance with EU law, contains provisions according to which contracts are to be concluded when competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.</seg>
<seg id="48">The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow contracting authorities to choose between open and restricted procedures.</seg>
<seg id="49">There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, including about 1,900 companies with 20 or more employees.</seg>
<seg id="50">Construction volume of contracting authorities and shares of the procurement types in both countries</seg>
<seg id="51">In Germany, the total construction volume in 2011 amounted to 307 billion euros.</seg>
<seg id="52">Of this amount, 45.5 billion euros were spent on public construction (15 %), which, in addition to federal construction, also includes the construction measures of the federal states and municipalities.</seg>
<seg id="53">The construction volume of the federal government in building construction and trunk road construction (excluding rail transport infrastructure and hydraulic engineering) amounted to 8.5 billion euros.</seg>
<seg id="54">In 2011, the volume of contracts for construction work in building construction and highway construction in the Federal Republic of Germany was distributed among the types of contracts as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public tenders, 12.7% restricted procedures and restricted tenders, and 6.6% negotiated procedures and open tenders.</seg>
<seg id="55">Of these, 33.2% were awarded Europe-wide.</seg>
<seg id="56">The volume of public construction projects in the Czech Republic amounted to 4.7 billion euros in 2011, which represented about 25% of the total volume of all construction projects in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="57">In 2009, the volume amounted to 7.8 billion euros, which represented 37% of the total construction volume.</seg>
<seg id="58">Breakdown by type of award for 2011: 65.1% open procedures 14.3% non-public procedures 9.5% negotiated procedures 8.4% simplified procedures for order volumes below the threshold 2.7% other procedures</seg>
<seg id="59">The data refer to all public contracts for supplies, services and works awarded by public procurement agencies in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="60">The above-mentioned data show that the parallel audits of both countries are directed towards a significant part of public procurement, the Prevention of corruption to be observed in all contracts has a great financial impact and the open procedure and the public tender are of outstanding importance in the award of contracts</seg>
<seg id="61">Summary of results of parallel tests</seg>
<seg id="62">The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (Nkú) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel audits in their countries on the EU-wide award of construction services and on corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="63">In this context, the working groups of both audit bodies compared the corresponding legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the areas of building construction and road construction.</seg>
<seg id="64">In doing so, they essentially stated::</seg>
<seg id="65">The EU directives on the award of works by contracting authorities have been transposed into national law in both the Czech Republic and Germany (no. 1 and 3.1).</seg>
<seg id="66">In addition to the EU regulations, the procurement regulations of both countries also serve to prevent corruption, which partly differ in their focus and in their detail (No. 3.2).</seg>
<seg id="67">In both countries, an essential requirement for the procurement documents is that they must contain all the information required for the proper preparation of tenders.</seg>
<seg id="68">The performance specifications must be neutral and must not have any restrictions on competition.</seg>
<seg id="69">In Germany, the procurement documents have largely met these requirements.</seg>
<seg id="70">In the Czech Republic, it is still a Problem to determine the subject of the contract sufficiently.</seg>
<seg id="71">In Germany, construction work must be divided into lots, if possible, in order to promote competition.</seg>
<seg id="72">According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement was largely implemented in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="73">The Nkú found in its tests, especially in the field of road construction, that the award of extensive services without lots or with only very large lots can affect competition and lead to a restriction to only a few large companies.</seg>
<seg id="74">Narrowing the market potential can result in significant cost increases and carry the risk of price or other agreements.</seg>
<seg id="75">In accordance with the provisions of both countries, the contracting authorities may, under certain conditions, agree in principle with the companies already commissioned additional or amended services that prove necessary after conclusion of the original contract (No. 4.1).</seg>
<seg id="76">The respective specifications for determining the type of award were largely followed in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="77">According to the regulations of the Czech Republic, the contracting authorities are free to choose between open and restricted procedures.</seg>
<seg id="78">In Germany, on the other hand, the legal and budgetary primacy of the open procedure applies to EU-wide contracts or the public tender, which corresponds to the open procedure for national contracts.</seg>
<seg id="79">This allows more companies to submit offers.</seg>
<seg id="80">This reduces the risk of corruption, complicates price agreements between bidders and leads to the most economical results.</seg>
<seg id="81">In the case of construction projects whose estimated total contract values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited building authorities awarded the construction services in principle throughout Europe.</seg>
<seg id="82">The correct estimation of the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.</seg>
<seg id="83">In Germany, cost databases are used for the cost determination of public buildings, especially in building construction,</seg>
<seg id="84">based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="85">In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective Instrument (No. 4.2).</seg>
<seg id="86">For construction works to be awarded throughout Europe, preliminary information and announcements must be published. This is intended to strengthen competition by enabling interested companies to adapt to the planned Awards at an early stage.</seg>
<seg id="87">As a rule, the audited building administrations complied with this requirement.</seg>
<seg id="88">In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or missing controls may affect competition (No. 4.3).</seg>
<seg id="89">The selection of candidates for participation in public procurement procedures is particularly susceptible to manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="90">According to EU law, the number of invited applicants must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.</seg>
<seg id="91">The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be announced in advance.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition to the requirements of the EU, the awarding authorities in both countries should switch between the companies to be invited as often as possible when selecting applicants.</seg>
<seg id="93">In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are sometimes very detailed specifications in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="94">The audited administrations disregarded these requirements in some cases.</seg>
<seg id="95">In the Czech Republic, decisions on the selection of candidates were not always comprehensible (No. 4.4).</seg>
<seg id="96">In both countries, in the interest of equal competition, it is necessary to ensure that the companies interested in submitting a bid receive the same information during the bidding phase.</seg>
<seg id="97">In order to avoid anticompetitive agreements, contact between these companies and with freelancers who were involved in the preparation of the service description must be avoided as far as possible.</seg>
<seg id="98">The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="99">The certified building authorities in Germany partially did not comply with these requirements (No. 4.5).</seg>
<seg id="100">When opening the offers in both countries, the multi-eye principle and the principle of transparency must be observed in particular.</seg>
<seg id="101">The specifications for the marking, documentation, safekeeping and confidentiality of the offers are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly detailed in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="102">The tests in both countries revealed only a few complaints (No. 4.6).</seg>
<seg id="103">Examination and evaluation of the offers are defined in both countries by requirements for the structure and process Organization.</seg>
<seg id="104">The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="105">For example, procurement agencies handed over offers for examination to third parties without having to look through the offers beforehand and sufficiently document abnormalities.</seg>
<seg id="106">The offers were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (No. 4.7).</seg>
<seg id="107">At the conclusion of the EU-wide procurement procedures, the companies involved in the competition should be informed of the intended assignment before the award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="108">This legal protection also has a preventive function against corrupt behaviour.</seg>
<seg id="109">The Czech Republic also provides for judicial review for non-EU-wide procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="110">Only in a few cases did the contracting authorities not comply with the specified deadlines for the award of contracts or deviated from the bidders ' offer in terms of content (No. 4.8).</seg>
<seg id="111">The documentation of the procurement procedures was not always complete or comprehensible with the audited building administrations in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="112">The EU-wide transparency requirement was not sufficiently implemented in the procurement notes of some procedures.</seg>
<seg id="113">Some of the shortcomings identified also reduced the anti-corruption function of the documentation.</seg>
<seg id="114">The contracting authorities of both countries largely fulfilled their reporting and reporting obligations (No. 4.9).</seg>
<seg id="115">Fundamentals of EU procurement law and Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="116">EU procurement law</seg>
<seg id="117">In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, among other things, the procurement coordination directive and the remedies directive, which had to be transposed into national law by the member states.</seg>
<seg id="118">The general procurement principles of the European Union are in particular the competition law, the Equal Treatment Law or the Prohibition of discrimination as well as the transparency law.</seg>
<seg id="119">In order to achieve these objectives, the procurement coordination directive contains special provisions for construction services to be awarded throughout the EU for construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="120">For this purpose, their estimated order amounts must reach or exceed a current volume of 5,000,000 euros.</seg>
<seg id="121">The regulations concern, in particular, documents the content of the Award, the publication of certain information before, during, and after the award, to Comply with deadlines, including for the receipt of tenders, the documentation of the procurement procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualifications of the applicants and The remedies Directive provides the basis for the legal protection of candidates and tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="122">In the event of possible infringements of Public Procurement Law, the companies concerned may have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review proceedings.</seg>
<seg id="123">Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the directives of the European Union into national law.</seg>
<seg id="124">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="125">Importance of preventing corruption</seg>
<seg id="126">In both countries there is no legal Definition of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="127">In general, corruption is the abuse of a position of trust for private benefit,</seg>
<seg id="128">which is usually initiated by the beneficiaries of these decisions.</seg>
<seg id="129">Corruption can impede competition and cause significant economic damage.</seg>
<seg id="130">It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of world economic output.</seg>
<seg id="131">For the European Union, the scale of these costs is estimated at 1%.</seg>
<seg id="132">In the case of public clients, restrictive agreements or unfair conduct may call into question trust in the integrity and functioning of the administration.</seg>
<seg id="133">Preventing corruption is therefore one of the fundamental tasks of public authorities.</seg>
<seg id="134">They have to check the structure and process Organization of their administrations for areas particularly at risk of corruption in order to make appropriate safeguards against corruption there.</seg>
<seg id="135">Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.</seg>
<seg id="136">The award of Public Works is generally regarded as a particularly corrupt field of work.</seg>
<seg id="137">Measures to prevent corruption</seg>
<seg id="138">In Germany, corruption – in particular bribery and bribery as well as acceptance and approval of benefits-is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.</seg>
<seg id="139">In order to prevent corruption, the federal government has adopted a directive and recommendations on the Prevention of Corruption12 in the federal administration. In addition to risk analysis, the following principles must be observed for the procurement area: priority of public tenders and open procedures, multi-eyes principle and transparency, fundamental separation of planning, awarding and billing, precise and complete documentation of the procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="140">In addition, further anti-corruption provisions have been incorporated into the procurement regulations.</seg>
<seg id="141">In 2011, for example, the Federal Ministry responsible for procurement in the area of federal highways introduced an electronically supported control system,</seg>
<seg id="142">with the award data − such as the estimated costs and the order totals-as well as information on the freelancers involved are collected comprehensively and evaluated for abnormalities.</seg>
<seg id="143">Corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="144">The legal requirements of transparency and equal treatment of bidders as well as the Prohibition of any discrimination form the most important foundations of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="145">For public procurement, the Czech government has defined anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper on combating corruption for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.</seg>
<seg id="146">Some of the measures recommended in it have already been transposed into national procurement law and corresponding administrative regulations.</seg>
<seg id="147">The new legislation contains essentially the following provisions: reduction of the thresholds for smaller contracts, obligation to publish the contracts in advance by the awarding authority, including the reasons for the tender, Prohibition of limiting the number of tenderers in restricted procedures and thus abolition of the possibility of selecting tenderers by lot, introduction of the obligation to publish the contract documents and all annexes, introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.</seg>
<seg id="148">Examination results for the individual phases of the award procedure</seg>
<seg id="149">Procurement documents</seg>
<seg id="150">Procurement documents the procurement documents must contain all the information that the bidders need for the proper preparation of the tender.</seg>
<seg id="151">In particular, the procurement documents must enable a correct calculation.</seg>
<seg id="152">No risks may be transferred to bidders that are not calculable for them.</seg>
<seg id="153">The procurement documents consist in particular of the service description and the contract conditions.</seg>
<seg id="154">In addition, they contain the specifications for proving the qualification (suitability) of the bidders as well as the criteria that are decisive for the selection of the most economical offer.</seg>
<seg id="155">Requirements of EU law and Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="156">The requirements of EU law for the procurement documents are directed in particular to the technical specifications.</seg>
<seg id="157">These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should limit competition as little as possible.</seg>
<seg id="158">The service description must be product-neutral.</seg>
<seg id="159">Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only permitted under strict conditions.</seg>
<seg id="160">The avoidance of restrictions on competition in the procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="161">In addition, unclear or incorrect information in the procurement documents must be avoided, as they open up scope for speculation when preparing the tenders and for manipulation of their valuation.</seg>
<seg id="162">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="163">Same or similar regulations in both countries, the EU legal requirements for the technical specifications have been transposed into national law.</seg>
<seg id="164">The services are generally product-neutral without specification.</seg>
<seg id="165">In the service descriptions, the individual services must usually be subdivided in detail into service units with respective quantities.</seg>
<seg id="166">The prices are to be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. Euro per m2 or per piece).</seg>
<seg id="167">Only in exceptional cases may performance be defined by functional targets.</seg>
<seg id="168">In any case, the service descriptions must be complete and unambiguous.</seg>
<seg id="169">They must contain precise quantities and must not include services for which it is not clear whether they are needed.</seg>
<seg id="170">Compensation according to flat rates or according to time expenditure must be avoided as far as possible.</seg>
<seg id="171">These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on unspecified specifications in the procurement documents.</seg>
<seg id="172">The service descriptions must enable the bidders to create their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.</seg>
<seg id="173">The tender shall only be made public when the tender documents have been completed.</seg>
<seg id="174">Differing regulations</seg>
<seg id="175">There is no obligation to tender for construction works in lots in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="176">If it is possible according to the type of service to be commissioned, the public procurement authorities may subdivide construction services into several lots.</seg>
<seg id="177">In Germany, construction services are generally to be divided into lots, separated by quantity (partial lots) and/ or by type or subject area (specialist lots).</seg>
<seg id="178">This should enable medium-sized companies to participate in the competition, expand the number of possible providers and make price agreements more difficult.</seg>
<seg id="179">This type of award is usually considered the most economical.</seg>
<seg id="180">In the Czech Republic, evaluation criteria must be indicated in the procurement documents for both EU-wide and national procedures.</seg>
<seg id="181">This should allow applicants to be fully and conclusively aware of the criteria according to which their offers are to be evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="182">In Germany, the specification of evaluation criteria in EU-wide notices, but at the latest in the procurement documents, is only required in EU-wide procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="183">In national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria are to be recorded only in an internal administrative procurement note.</seg>
<seg id="184">Procurement documents drawn up by authorised freelancers may not contain references to these offices or involved planners or experts in Germany with the building construction and some road construction administrations.</seg>
<seg id="185">This is intended to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages without the knowledge of the client through contact with these freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="186">This is also the reason why freelance procurement documents may neither send nor interpret planning documents for inspection.</seg>
<seg id="187">The contact person of the companies is solely the client.</seg>
<seg id="188">There is currently no regulation on this in the Czech Republic.</seg>
<seg id="189">Additional or amended services that prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements) are almost always required for large construction projects.</seg>
<seg id="190">In both countries, the statutory provisions allow, to a certain extent, the award of supplements to the company already commissioned, without the need for a public procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="191">According to the EU regulations and the German regulations, the remuneration of the supplementary services may not exceed half of the main contract.</seg>
<seg id="192">In addition, the additional services must not be separated from the main order without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.</seg>
<seg id="193">In the Czech Republic, a narrower limit of 20% applies for a corresponding award without public notice.</seg>
<seg id="194">However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already underway.</seg>
<seg id="195">If supplementary services are also transferred to the already commissioned company, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is generally not possible under the regulations in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="196">In determining the remuneration for the additional services, the agreed prices and the basis of the price determination of the order already issued must be assumed.</seg>
<seg id="197">In addition to supplementary benefits, there may also be a reduction in the scope of benefits.</seg>
<seg id="198">In the Czech Republic, reduced quantities cannot be offset against additional additional services.</seg>
<seg id="199">Essential Examination Results</seg>
<seg id="200">BHR</seg>
<seg id="201">Technical specifications and product-neutral tender</seg>
<seg id="202">In individual cases, the service descriptions contained references to national technical approvals or standards that had already been replaced by Europe-wide standards.</seg>
<seg id="203">Some performance descriptions also contained product-related specifications – for example for graffiti protection, joint tapes or noise protection panels-without this being necessary.</seg>
<seg id="204">In some cases, performance requirements were described so accurately that only one product was eligible.</seg>
<seg id="205">Tables of services broken down according to partial services</seg>
<seg id="206">The BRH has not found in any of the audited procedures violations of the requirement to tender services in principle in a list of services subdivided according to partial services.</seg>
<seg id="207">Completeness of the service descriptions</seg>
<seg id="208">In the vast majority of the procedures, the procurement documents were completed before the start of the tenders.</seg>
<seg id="209">In some procedures, the procurement documents had to be corrected during the tender phase, as some positions or deadlines had changed.</seg>
<seg id="210">In some cases, the service lists contained items that did not determine whether they were needed.</seg>
<seg id="211">A list of services for demolition work even consisted almost half of such demand items.</seg>
<seg id="212">Lots and evaluation criteria</seg>
<seg id="213">With many awards, the prescribed reason was missing, why the predominantly after unprofessional advertised services were not further divided into partial lots.</seg>
<seg id="214">There were no complaints when specifying the criteria to be used in the evaluation of the offers.</seg>
<seg id="215">References to freelancers</seg>
<seg id="216">A small part of the service descriptions contained references to the involved freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="217">Their names were partly on the covers or in attached plans or reports.</seg>
<seg id="218">In one case, the awarding authority even explicitly asked the applicants to contact the architect "on questions of the tender".</seg>
<seg id="219">In the building sector in particular, the contracting authorities attributed the complaints mentioned predominantly to the failures of the freelancers commissioned with the preparation of the service descriptions.</seg>
<seg id="220">The Construction Services pointed out the lack of capacities in order to be able to adequately control the service descriptions.</seg>
<seg id="221">NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="222">Technical specifications and product-neutral tender in the public procurement for the construction of a residential building with 12 residential units, a supplier and a specific product brand were specified in the service description.</seg>
<seg id="223">The awarding authority did not allow the use of comparable products without justifying this.</seg>
<seg id="224">During the construction of several university buildings, suppliers and products were also specified in the tender.</seg>
<seg id="225">Performance descriptions with performance units</seg>
<seg id="226">In the case of construction projects in some industrial areas, the awarding authority did not clearly specify the scope and type of services required in the specifications.</seg>
<seg id="227">As performance units, it only specified the converted space of the individual buildings in cubic meters.</seg>
