<seg id="730">In other proceedings in Germany, tenderers can only be informed of the award decision after the award of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="731">In the Czech Republic, a procurement procedure must be terminated if only one offer has been received or only one offer has been evaluated.</seg>
<seg id="732">In Germany, the contract must also be awarded in the case of only one valuable tender, provided that it complies with the terms of the tender and is economically viable.</seg>
<seg id="733">Essential Examination Results</seg>
<seg id="734">BRH</seg>
<seg id="735">There were only a few complaints about the audited contracts at the end of the procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="736">In some cases, companies received letters of order for EU-wide contracts before the expiry of the information periods, which may result in the ineffectiveness of the contract.</seg>
<seg id="737">In individual cases, Order letters also contained content that deviated from the content of the offer, such as changed dates.</seg>
<seg id="738">In several cases, the clients did not comply with the award deadlines.</seg>
<seg id="739">In an open procedure, a contracting authority therefore awarded the contract for the second cheapest offer, since a company with a 50% cheaper offer was no longer willing to perform the services at the originally offered price after the expiry of the contract period.</seg>
<seg id="740">NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="741">In the case of a construction project in the higher education sector, the contracting authority deviated from the bidder's offer in terms of content.</seg>
<seg id="742">For some contracts, for example for the construction of road maintenance, for the construction of a motorway and a bypass, the contracting authorities concluded the contracts after expiry of the statutory period.</seg>
<seg id="743">In the case of the award of works for the renovation of former military sites, the awarding authority forwarded the notification of the award of the contract to all bidders only after expiry of the statutory period.</seg>
<seg id="744">Summary Findings</seg>
<seg id="745">Both countries have implemented the EU guidelines at the conclusion of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="746">The legal protection of the unsuccessful candidates or tenderers increases the instruments of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="747">The scope of legal protection in Czech procurement law is also extended to contracts below the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="748">In both countries, the deadlines for placing orders were exceeded.</seg>
<seg id="749">This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="750">In the future, the building authorities should avoid the identified defects when concluding their procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="751">Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations</seg>
<seg id="752">The award procedures must be comprehensibly documented during their individual stages with regard to the relevant findings as well as the justifications of the individual decisions.</seg>
<seg id="753">For EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded must be made known.</seg>
<seg id="754">The order data are also recorded in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of EU law and Prevention of corruption by documenting the procurement procedures, a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement is implemented.</seg>
<seg id="756">A carefully and promptly prepared documentation only enables the traceability of the procurement decisions.</seg>
<seg id="757">In particular, it also serves the effective legal protection of bidders in the case of contracts above the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential component to avoid corruption, since the compulsion to justify procurement decisions in detail significantly restricts scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">The contract notice for an EU-wide procurement procedure has to be sent by the respective contracting authority to the office for official publications of the EU within 48 days.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU and thus also implements the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting authorities must also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the EU Commission via the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the EU Commission draws up an annual EU statistics, through which it can obtain an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.</seg>
<seg id="763">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Same or similar regulations</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed the EU legal requirements for documentation and reporting obligations into national law.</seg>
<seg id="766">The rules for documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Differing regulations</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish contracts awarded is not limited to EU-wide contracts, but also extends to other procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The publication period is shortened to 15 days.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, in addition to the EU-wide awards, there is a publication obligation only for restricted tenders and for free-handed awards above value limits of 25,000 euros or 15,000 euros without VAT (so-called Ex-post Transparency).</seg>
<seg id="771">Below these value limits, as well as in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition procedure receive information about the orders placed.</seg>
<seg id="772">Essential Examination Results</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of the audited procurement procedures were not fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The procurement notes did not contain all the necessary information, such as the justification of product specifications or references to national regulations.</seg>
<seg id="777">In a procurement procedure, the awarding authority did not explain why it awarded the contract to a company, even though its offer did not contain mandatory evidence.</seg>
<seg id="778">In a few cases, the documents of the awarding authorities did not contain all the evidence required for the documentation of the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="779">Notices of orders</seg>
<seg id="780">In some EU-wide procurement procedures, the contracting authorities failed to make the awarding of contracts public.</seg>
<seg id="781">In the case of further procurement procedures, there was no evidence that the contracting authorities had made the awarded contracts public.</seg>
<seg id="782">Reporting and reporting obligations</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistical tables consulted contained the required minimum information. They were drawn up and sent on schedule.</seg>
<seg id="784">Ex-post Transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">In most cases, the audited building authorities published the order data of the completed procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="786">However, due to a transmission error, this data was not published in a construction administration.</seg>
<seg id="787">The construction management noticed this error only after half a year,</seg>
<seg id="788">so that the order data of the procurement procedures completed up to that time were not published.</seg>
<seg id="789">NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">In the case of construction work for the organisation of a major sporting event, the documentation of the award procedures showed considerable shortcomings. These were mainly incorrect information, such as incorrect offer prices in the minutes of the valuation commissions.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some minutes of the openings were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Notices of orders</seg>
<seg id="794">In the case of several road construction projects, notices of contracts awarded were only published late or not at all.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary Findings</seg>
<seg id="796">The regulations on documentation and reporting and reporting requirements are largely identical in both countries and implement the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="797">The transparency of the procurement procedures, including the award of contracts, is thereby guaranteed in principle.</seg>
<seg id="798">The regulations to be applied in the Czech Republic for publication go somewhat further than the requirements in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="799">The deficiencies identified in the documentation and in the notices partially substantially limited the orruption - preventing effect of these instruments in the respective procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="800">This segment ISIN tention ally left blank</seg>
<seg id="801">The building authorities should further improve the transparency of their procurement procedures and orders and fully comply with their reporting and reporting obligations.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">The parallel tests carried out by the NKÚ and BRH focused on two main areas that are essential for the award of construction services by public authorities in the Czech Republic and Germany: the application of EU procurement rules and the Prevention of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="804">The requirements of EU law enable cross-border competition to create a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Anti-corruption measures do not only serve to prevent or at least reduce corruption. You should also avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two courts of auditors on the application of public procurement rules in both countries, as well as the comparison of these rules, provide information on similarities and differences that can be helpful for both countries in the further development of their public procurement law and its application.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement rules</seg>
<seg id="808">Both countries have transposed the EU requirements for the award of construction services into national law.</seg>
<seg id="809">This means that in the Czech Republic and Germany there is an important common basis for the award of construction services and the consideration of the essential requirements of competition, equal treatment of the participating companies and transparency of the award procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">The building administrations of both countries have partially supported these bids very extensively by further administrative regulations.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has to a large extent also transferred the specifications for the construction services to be awarded throughout the EU to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, the court of auditors ' investigations have shown that the building authorities have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.</seg>
<seg id="813">The construction administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to eliminate the complaints identified when implementing the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">The tests in the Czech Republic have shown above all risks that affect the economic viability of the contracts.</seg>
<seg id="815">Thus, incomplete service descriptions made additional services necessary, which were often awarded in violation of legal regulations. In addition, the cost assessments were usually insufficiently prepared. Excessive qualification requirements also reduced the number of potential bidders and restricted competition, particularly in the transport sector.</seg>
<seg id="816">Prevention of corruption</seg>
<seg id="817">The investigations have not had the goal of uncovering corruption cases,</seg>
<seg id="818">also because the courts of auditors do not have the appropriate instruments for this.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, the courts of auditors can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and Manipulation in the award of construction services and how these requirements are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">Both countries have set different priorities in preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="821">Above all, the German regulations provide for largely unrestricted competition as well as transparency and controls as central elements of preventing corruption.</seg>
<seg id="822">The Czech regulations aim above all at increased transparency of procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, general principles of prevention of corruption apply, which the entire federal administration has to apply.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of construction services and are geared to their special requirements.</seg>
<seg id="826">In some cases, the corresponding Regulations specify very precisely how the bids for corruption prevention are to be taken into account when the procurement procedures are completed and when the persons involved are selected.</seg>
<seg id="827">In the view of the BRH, the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tender is a suitable Instrument in order to significantly reduce the risk of corruption in the award of construction services. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative interventions.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analyses and sufficient controls (especially the multi-eyes principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures as well as various organizational measures are also effective precautions to prevent corruption and Manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The BRH therefore sees no fundamental need to change the corresponding specifications of the administrations when awarding construction services.</seg>
<seg id="830">The regulations for preventing corruption are largely taken into account in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">The shortcomings identified in some areas have highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some specifications.</seg>
<seg id="832">The building authorities should further train their employees on the requirements for corruption prevention and raise them even more awareness of this problem.</seg>
<seg id="833">A substantial part of the complaints related to tasks delegated by the building authorities to freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, without controls and sufficient safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.</seg>
<seg id="835">Therefore, tasks at risk of manipulation and corruption should only be entrusted to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient level of protection against inadmissible interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="837">At government level, the Czech Republic adopted a strategy against corruption, in which public procurement is the most important component.</seg>
<seg id="838">The Procurement Act and its implementing rules have been substantially amended.</seg>
<seg id="839">The audits of the NKÚ took place during the implementation of this strategy.</seg>
<seg id="840">The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions are likely to be effective improvement measures, since the contracting authorities must justify the cost-effectiveness of the orders, the calculation of the expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the type of evaluations, and properly document and publish all these aspects.</seg>
<seg id="841">Make recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">The NKÚ and the BRH assess the implementation of the EU requirements in principle positively.</seg>
<seg id="843">The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU's requirements of competition, equal treatment and transparency are a suitable basis for the award of construction services within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="844">The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting cross-border competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">In view of the enormous material and immaterial damage potential caused by Manipulation and corruption in the award of construction services, both courts of auditors see the building authorities in their countries as being called upon to continue and, if necessary, improve their measures against corruption and Manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, the Organisation and procedures of the procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to initiate appropriate countermeasures.</seg>
<seg id="847">The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures offer a wider scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="848">A greater division of construction services into lots can also have a favourable effect on the offer prices, provided that this leads to greater competition with a higher number of bidders.</seg>
<seg id="849">Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for the efficient procurement activities of contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised building administrations. In the Czech Republic, on the other hand, these tasks – with the exception of transport construction projects – are performed by the departments themselves or by contractors commissioned by them.</seg>
<seg id="851">The courts of Auditors of both countries have the intention, even after the completion of their joint project, to further develop the relevant findings for them and, if necessary, to refer them to the parliament and government of their country.</seg>
<seg id="852">Both audit bodies are also convinced that the principles of procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at the international level of the International Organization of supreme audit institutions (INTOSAI). This is because the principles and findings set out are of general importance in order to effectively combat corruption and to ensure the economic allocation of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.</seg>
