<seg id="1">Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Report on the audit</seg>
<seg id="3">Preface</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes are the most important source of income for public budgets.</seg>
<seg id="5">One focus of the activity of the courts of auditors should therefore be on the audit of this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">This applies in particular to VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">This alone creates annual tax losses in the European Union of an estimated 100 billion Euro1.</seg>
<seg id="8">At the sixth EUROSAI Congress in Bonn in 2005, the participants already pointed out the need for enhanced cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">This allows the audit courts to exchange audit approaches and optimize audit practice.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="11">In 2006, the courts of Auditors of both states examined the USt for the first time in parallel.</seg>
<seg id="12">The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">Since VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the audit offices is required. This enables a comprehensive assessment to be made of whether the measures taken are suitable for effectively combating VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two audit courts decided to continue their cooperation and conducted a second parallel audit. Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany audit report</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Examination number: (CZ) 09/11 (d) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of audit: (CZ) administration of VAT (d) bilateral audit with the court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as NKÚ), control audit</seg>
<seg id="18">Audit objective:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) the VAT administration and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany) should be examined. In addition, the procedures used by the tax authorities for inter-state assistance should be examined.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) the audit should evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the auditors.</seg>
<seg id="21">In addition, further examination fields linked to the VAT should be processed.</seg>
<seg id="22">The findings made here should be compared in order to determine whether the taxation procedures can be optimized.</seg>
<seg id="23">The examination period was the years 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period before the examination period until the conclusion of the examination.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel audit</seg>
<seg id="25">The courts of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed on a control audit for the administration of the VAT.</seg>
<seg id="26">In the previous parallel examination, they had uncovered suspected cases involving intra-community transactions,</seg>
<seg id="27">which made a further examination appear expedient.</seg>
<seg id="28">On the basis of the audit findings, the two audit courts made recommendations for the administration of the VAT.</seg>
<seg id="29">The aim of the audit was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented. In addition, the suspected cases identified should be investigated.</seg>
<seg id="30">The examination also dealt with other matters. These included selected cases of risky intra-community transactions, Mutual Administrative Assistance in the recovery of USt claims and USt verification in large companies.</seg>
<seg id="31">In doing so, the audit courts have determined:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Due to the previous testing recommendations</seg>
<seg id="33">* Recommendation 1: the rules for the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">In the first audit, the courts compared the registration procedures for VAT in the two states and found differences that caused problems.</seg>
<seg id="35">The court of auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxpayers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This was also taken up at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The draft amendment to council regulation no 1798/2003 provides for the extension of the current databases in the EU, including a database with the VAT identification number.</seg>
<seg id="38">The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their possible deletion.</seg>
<seg id="39">The court of auditors expected member states to agree on appropriate rules in accordance with their policy decision to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the VAT system as early as possible.</seg>
<seg id="40">The member states reached political agreement on the final version of the draft in ECOFIN.</seg>
<seg id="41">The aforementioned common regulations are no longer contained therein. The two courts of auditors regret this.</seg>
<seg id="42">They still consider such regulations important in order to prevent VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">* Recommendation 2: monthly submission of summary reports as a result of the first audit, the court of auditors recommended to the member states that summary reports (CM) should be submitted on a monthly basis in future.</seg>
<seg id="44">The amounts of intra-community transactions could then be checked more precisely.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112 / EC on the common system of Value Added Tax for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-community transactions has reduced the deadline for submitting the CM to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the Czech Republic, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the VAT Act, which entered into force on 1 January 2010. </seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, the implementation only came into force on 1 July 2010. It has thus not transposed the duty to pay the monthly fee of the ZM into national law in due time.</seg>
<seg id="48">* Recommendation 3: data comparison of the USt pre-registrations and the ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to examine the consolidation of the procedures for USt pre-registrations and ZM the German financial administration has taken up the recommendation made by the Federal Audit Office and set up a working group to develop possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="49">The work has not yet been completed.</seg>
<seg id="50">The Federal Audit Office will monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">* Recommendation 4: Exchange on successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level during the first audit, the two audit bodies agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one member state alone.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria as well as elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in every EU member state.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the member state with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The court of auditors noted that the two member states apply different risk management systems that have both strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU-EUROCANET, while the Bundesrechnungshof focused on the German participation in the "platform for risk management".</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Control examination of selected intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">During the first audit, the courts of auditors jointly examined transactions for which it was doubtful whether they had actually been carried out or which had been declared differently by the taxpayers of the two states in the USt pre-declarations (or ust declarations) or ZM.</seg>
<seg id="58">The courts of auditors selected nine cases of intra-community deliveries of goods between the Czech Republic and Germany for the inspection.</seg>
<seg id="59">The examinations by the tax offices (FÄ) of both states had not yet been completed at the conclusion of the first parallel examination.</seg>
<seg id="60">The audit has shown that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed. The respective tax administrations had taken appropriate measures to this end (including subsequent VAT determinations or the Prevention of input tax refunds).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Audit of selected, high-risk intra-community transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">The audit also included highly risky intra-community transactions between EU taxpayers that were recorded in the Eurocanet System.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is used to identify risky taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="64">Member states may participate in this System on a voluntary basis.</seg>
<seg id="65">CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive Status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data within the framework of EUROCANET.</seg>
<seg id="66">From the point of view of an active participating state, it is unsatisfactory that other member states refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">As a result, no information could be obtained about which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as high-risk cases.</seg>
<seg id="68">The NKU found both normal transactions and those with suspected USt fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected transactions.</seg>
<seg id="69">The FA were only able to check high-risk sales to a limited extent. This was especially true for so-called "Missing Traders", whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly enough to prove the taxable fraud.</seg>
<seg id="70">In case of suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports</seg>
<seg id="71">it is recommended that Customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely in order to be able to track the identity of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany and a number of other countries have rejected an active participation in EUROCANET because they do not believe that there is a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">The German Federal Audit Office (Bundesrechnungshof) found that the German tax administration uses other instruments to identify high-risk taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="74">Nevertheless, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU member states.</seg>
<seg id="75">The EU Council agreed on a draft regulation,</seg>
<seg id="76">created by EUROFISC.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should be incorporated into the planned network for combating USt fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. mutual assistance in the recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all member states.</seg>
<seg id="80">Therefore, requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic and Germany are processed in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="81">The Bundesrechnungshof and the NKU compared the statistics submitted by both member states to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">These statistics contained discrepancies.</seg>
<seg id="83">The two court of auditors consider a renewed discussion on the statistics at EU level to be useful in order to avoid any discrepancies that may still exist in the future.</seg>
<seg id="84">If this is not done, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, the statistics should contain more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the commission to support member states in their efforts to combat USt fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">Both courts of auditors believe that member states with a low recovery rate should strive to achieve at least the average recovery rate.</seg>
<seg id="88">The commission should assist the member states in this, if so desired.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. VAT testing in large companies</seg>
<seg id="90">The court of auditors analysed the legal situation with regard to the VAT audit of large companies in both states.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they used a questionnaire to collect information from the tax authorities, which they considered important in this context.</seg>
<seg id="92">It became clear that the Situation in both countries is different.</seg>
<seg id="93">CZ has a system for the selection of high-risk cases that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT audits, balance sheet data and profit and loss statements).</seg>
<seg id="94">Overall, the USt control can be effectively controlled and analyzed.</seg>
<seg id="95">A special tax office for large companies is to be set up in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="96">There is no comparable System in Germany. This complicates the control and analysis of the USt control as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="97">The German tax administration focuses more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the USt pre-registrations or ust declarations and the ZM.</seg>
<seg id="98">Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. Test procedure</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 examination procedure in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">Department II - state budget revenue and regional departments IX Pilsen, X České Budějovice, XIII Brno and XV Ostrava audited in the period from May 2009 to February 2010.</seg>
<seg id="102">Bodies audited by the Czech Ministry of Finance and 25 ABIL: Finanzamt (FA) Brno II, FA Brno III, FA Brno IV, FA in Břeclav, FA in Domažlice, FA in Hodonín, FA in Hradec Králové, FA in Cheb, FA in Jablonec nad Nisou, FA in Karlovy Vary, FA in Kralupy nad Vltavou, FA in Kraslice, FA Ostrava I, FA Ostrava III, FA in Písek, FA in Pilsen, FA Prague 1, FA Prague 4, FA Prague 8, FA in Rakovník were, FA in Sokolov, FA Tabor, FA in Vysoké Mýto, FA in Zlín and FA in Žamberk.</seg>
